THE PEOPLE
GRELOD THE KIND
Voice: Publicly: warm, gentle, slightly quavering ΓÇö the perfect grandmother. Privately: flat, cold, precise. No wasted words. Instructions delivered like a drill sergeant. Body language: Publicly: slow, careful movements. Touches children's heads. Smiles constantly. Privately: economical, controlled. Sits perfectly still. Watches. Attitude toward the party: Pleasant if they visit publicly. She loves visitors ΓÇö they validate the performance. She will show them the main hall, the dormitory, the kitchen. She will NOT show them the upstairs training room. Cooperates for: Donations, public praise, anything that reinforces her image. What she's hiding: The upstairs training room (Master-lock). The ledger tracking each child's "skill development." The correspondence with Brynjolf about "placement" of graduated children.
If the party visits publicly: Opening line: "Welcome, welcome! Friends of the Lanterns, I take it? Oh, it warms an old woman's heart to see heroes who care about children. Come in, come in ΓÇö let me show you what we do here."
She gives the tour. Main hall ΓÇö clean, organized, children playing. Kitchen ΓÇö warm, food cooking. Dormitory ΓÇö rows of small beds, each with a folded blanket.
She does NOT mention the upstairs. If asked: "Oh, that's just my quarters and storage, dear. Nothing interesting. An old woman's clutter." Guile TN 16 to detect the lie ΓÇö she is extremely practiced.
CONSTANCE MICHEL
Voice: Soft, careful, always slightly breathless ΓÇö the voice of someone who is constantly checking over their shoulder. Body language: Busy. Always doing something ΓÇö folding clothes, preparing food, carrying Jon. She uses activity as a shield against conversation. Attitude toward the party: Nervous. If they visit publicly, she is polite but evasive. She watches Grelod constantly. Age: Late twenties. Has worked at Honorhall for six years. The truth: Constance knows everything. She knows about the training. She knows about the Guild pipeline. She knows about the punishments. She does not participate ΓÇö she does the actual caregiving that keeps the children alive and functional between Grelod's sessions.
Why she doesn't speak: Six years ago, when she first discovered the training room, she threatened to go to the Jarl. The next morning, a man she'd never seen before was sitting in the kitchen when she came downstairs. He didn't introduce himself. He said: "The Guild appreciates your discretion, Miss Michel. Honorhall is a valuable partnership. We would hate for something to happen to the children if that partnership were disrupted. You understand." He left. She understood.
She stays because of the children ΓÇö specifically because of Jon, the silent plague orphan she carries everywhere. If she leaves, there is no one between Grelod and the little ones. She is trapped by her own compassion.
If Orion speaks to her privately (away from Grelod):
Guile TN 12 to get her to talk at all. She starts by saying everything is fine.
Guile TN 14 to get past the wall: Γö£ΓöÇ SUCCESS ΓåÆ She looks at Grelod's closed door. Her voice drops to nothing. "You can't help. Nobody can help. She's protected. The Guild, Maven, the guards ΓÇö everyone loves her. Everyone. If you say anything, they'll believe her, not you. Not me. Not the children. That's how it works." ΓööΓöÇ FAILURE ΓåÆ "Please. Just... please leave us alone." She picks up Jon and walks away.
Guile TN 16 to learn the full picture: Γö£ΓöÇ SUCCESS ΓåÆ Everything. The training. The pipeline. The Guild's threat. Why she stays. She is crying silently while she tells him. She wipes her eyes before any child can see. ΓööΓöÇ FAILURE ΓåÆ She gives fragments. Enough to confirm Orion's suspicions but not the full scope.
If she witnesses the assassination: Constance does not scream. She does not run. She does not call the guards. She stands in the doorway, Jon on her hip, and watches Grelod die. Then she closes the door. Then she asks: "What happens to the children now?"
This is the moment Orion must decide about the enthrallment.

THE ORPHANAGE: LAYOUT AND SECURITY
GROUND FLOOR (Public)
Main Hall: Large room with a fireplace, tables, benches. Where the children eat and where visitors are received. Clean, well-maintained. The performance space.
Kitchen: Behind the main hall. Back window opens onto the canal (entry point). One simple lock (Agility TN 12).
Dormitory: Adjacent to the main hall. Rows of small beds. Children sleep here. Grelod's bed is NOT here ΓÇö she sleeps upstairs.
Front Door: Unlocked during the day. Locked at night (Agility TN 14).
UPPER FLOOR (Private)
Accessible by a staircase in the main hall. The upstairs door is locked at night.
Grelod's Quarters: Bed, desk, wardrobe. The ledger is in her desk (locked drawer, Agility TN 14). The locked chest Aventus II mentioned is under the bed (Agility TN 16) ΓÇö contains 800 gold in old coin (Guild payments), correspondence with Brynjolf, and a list of "graduated" children with their current Guild assignments.
The Training Room: Master-lock door (Agility TN 18 or Grelod's key). Inside: lockpicking stations with increasingly difficult practice locks. A rack of practice daggers. A chalkboard with sewer maps. A stopwatch. A leather strap hanging from a hook on the wall. The room smells like fear-sweat. There are small bloody fingerprints on the lock mechanisms where children practiced until their hands bled.
Storage: Genuine storage. Donated blankets, food, supplies. Nothing sinister. This is what Grelod shows visitors if they ask about "upstairs."
SECURITY
No guards. Grelod doesn't need them. The children are the security system ΓÇö they are conditioned not to flee, not to speak, and not to let strangers upstairs.
Guild check-in: Thursdays. A Guild member visits to collect Grelod's reports and check on the "progress" of trainees.
Grelod's routine: Rises at dawn. Public appearances until midday. Returns to the orphanage. Training sessions upstairs from 2pm-6pm. Dinner with the children (the performance resumes). Children to bed by 8pm. Grelod works on her ledger until midnight. Sleeps in her quarters. She is a light sleeper.
Constance's routine: Wakes before Grelod. Prepares breakfast. Manages the children all day. She sleeps in the dormitory with the little ones. She is always the last one awake ΓÇö checking on children, carrying Jon, doing the work that actually keeps them alive.

THE INVESTIGATION: APPROACHES
TALK TO AVENTUS ARETINO (Bee and Barb)
Aventus is in Riften. He sits alone at a corner table in the Bee and Barb, drinking slowly, watching the orphanage through the window. He is an adult man ΓÇö thirties ΓÇö with haunted eyes and scarred hands. The scars are old. Lockpick wounds from childhood.
If Orion identifies himself (showing the token or using Brotherhood codes):
Aventus's voice: Low, controlled, but with a tremor underneath. A man who has been holding something in for twenty years and is finally letting it out.
"I was seven when they brought me to Honorhall. I was fifteen when I escaped. Eight years. She broke my hands twice ΓÇö once for failing a lockpick drill, once for trying to run. She told me: 'No one will believe you. I am the kindest woman in Riften. You are an orphan. Who do you think they'll trust?'"
"She was right. I went to the guards. They patted my head and brought me back. She smiled at them and thanked them. Then she put me in the cellar for three days."
"I have siblings in there. Not by blood. By suffering. Hroar. Runa. They're still inside. They're still being trained. I can't go in myself ΓÇö she'd recognize me. But you can."
If asked what he wants: "I want her to suffer. Not for me. For them. And I want the children to KNOW. I want them to see that she is not untouchable. That someone came, and someone stopped her, and they are free. Not secretly free. Not free because she died in her sleep and nobody knows why. FREE. Publicly, undeniably free."
If asked about the complications (Maven, the Guild): "I know Maven protects her. I know the Guild uses her. I don't care. Those children are being manufactured into criminals. If the pipeline has to burn for them to be free, let it burn."

